(13. Understanding Embark in GNU Emacs \(a bit\) and some 'stupid' Embark tricks) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-06-09T03:46:37Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/programming/EmacsUnderstandingEmbark) Tj
T*
(When I wrote about the Emacs packages I use , I mentioned that I had Embark installed but) Tj
T*
(barely used it because I didn't understand much about how to really use it. One reason for that) Tj
T*
(is that while there are a bunch of articles on the web about things you can do with Embark, all) Tj
T*
(of the ones I've tried to read started out with complicated stuff involving other third party) Tj
T*
(packages I didn't use, which caused me to tune out and stop reading. As sometimes happens,) Tj
T*
(writing that entry caused me to poke at Embark some more and now I have a somewhat better) Tj
T*
(understanding of it and some Embark tricks I want to remember. \(Now that I've made the effort) Tj
T*
(to read it, Fifteen ways to use Embark has a bunch of useful examples that use only built in) Tj
T*
(packages. Also, part of my confusion is that Embark actually does multiple things.\) With) Tj
T*
(Embark, you start with a 'something' \(what Embark calls a target \) and then Embark lets you to) Tj
T*
(do an assortment of things to it; some Embark writeups describe this as a middle mouse button) Tj
T*
(context menu. There are at least two ways to get the 'something' \( cf \). In a regular buffer,) Tj
T*
(it's whatever is at point \(or the region if you have one active\); in the minibuffer...) Tj
T*
() Tj
