(14. Forms of Open Source Government) Tj
T*
(Source: Andrew Nesbitt | Published: 2026-06-09T10:00:00+00:00) Tj
T*
(Link: https://nesbitt.io/2026/06/09/forms-of-open-source-government.html) Tj
T*
(Benevolent dictator for life. The founder keeps final say over project direction in perpetuity,) Tj
T*
(by convention rather than written rule. Python ran this way until Guido stepped down in 2018,) Tj
T*
(and Linux, Ruby, Rails, and Laravel still do. The unspoken upper bound on ?in perpetuity? is) Tj
T*
(one human lifespan, which none of the famous projects in the category have had to test yet.) Tj
T*
(Malevolent dictator for life. The same arrangement after the benevolence has worn off, with the) Tj
T*
(founder still in the chair and nobody around with the access or the energy to do much about it.) Tj
T*
(From outside it shows up as long-time contributors going quiet and forks appearing in places) Tj
T*
(that do not usually fork. Steering council. What a BDFL project becomes after the dictator) Tj
T*
(retires or is asked to. The usual shape is a small elected committee with rotating seats and no) Tj
T*
(permanent membership, as in Python?s transition to a five-person Steering Council via PEP 13) Tj
T*
(and PEP 8016 after Guido stepped down. Most BDFL projects do not write a succession plan in) Tj
T*
(advance and end up improvising one in whatever crisis prompted the handover. Permanent core) Tj
T*
(team. A long-lived group of recognised maintainers joined by invitation and...) Tj
T*
() Tj
